=== Not Supported Features ===
- Connection timeout configuration: JDBC connection timeout is set at URL level, not per-connection
- Get active host: JDBC does not expose active host information like node-cubrid
- Query handle management: JDBC uses Statement/ResultSet objects, not query handles like node-cubrid
- Multiple queries require explicit ResultSet close: JDBC requires explicit ResultSet.close() for each query, node-cubrid auto-manages query handles
- Get autocommit mode: JDBC getAutoCommit() exists but requires callback conversion, node-cubrid provides sync getter
- Get engine version: JDBC does not expose CUBRID engine version directly like node-cubrid.getEngineVersion()
- Old query protocol: JDBC does not expose protocol selection, node-cubrid allows setEnforceOldQueryProtocol()
- Broker info: JDBC does not expose broker information (protocolVersion, etc.) like node-cubrid
- LOB types (BLOB/CLOB): JDBC LOB handling is different from node-cubrid lobRead/lobWrite methods
- Get schema (getSchema): JDBC uses DatabaseMetaData, node-cubrid provides getSchema() method
- Database parameters (getDatabaseParameter): JDBC does not expose CUBRID-specific database parameters like node-cubrid
- Set database parameters (setDatabaseParameter): JDBC does not expose CUBRID-specific database parameter setting
- batchExecuteNoQuery method: node-cubrid batchExecuteNoQuery() method not available in JDBC, use addBatch/executeBatch instead
- Connection events: node-cubrid emits events (connect, disconnect, error), JDBC uses callbacks only
- Socket access (_socket property): node-cubrid exposes _socket, JDBC does not expose underlying socket
- Query result set management: node-cubrid uses _queryResultSets object, JDBC requires explicit ResultSet management
- Typed parameters method: node-cubrid executeWithTypedParams() not available, JDBC uses setInt/setString/etc methods
- queryAll method: node-cubrid queryAll() method not available in JDBC
- fetch method for cursor: node-cubrid fetch() method not available, JDBC uses ResultSet.next()

